column67: Some libraries or code syntax demands a higher version of interpreter, and sometimes it cannot be polyfilled. In that situation, fixing the backport may break the intended use cases.

column67: rolling back is not possible when live data plays into it.  If there is a hot back up it works but is tricky.  When there is no hot back up it cannot be done.

I wouldn't say unable so much as unwilling. Fixes can generally be back ported with enough effort, regardless of dependencies (e.g. you can usually inline the dependencies with the necessary fixes). However, the reality of diminishing returns can often make it better to forgo a particular fix if it's too difficult.
